yrian President Bashar Assad in the Malkeh district of Damascus, Syria, on Sunday." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 People search for belongings in the ransacked private residence of Syrian President Bashar Assad in the Malkeh district of Damascus, Syria, on Sunday.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Hussein Malla/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The swift &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/02/nx-s1-5211873/hts-islamist-syria-aleppo-assad-hayat-tahrir-al-sham"&gt;rebel campaign&lt;/a&gt; started less than two weeks ago, when fighters launched a series of lightning offensives — first capturing the northern city of Aleppo and then advancing south toward the regime centers of power, as uprisings broke out in large swaths of the country.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
