mg" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1000/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 1000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1300/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 1300w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/2000/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 2000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/2600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg 2600w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 1238px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 60px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F9c%2F39%2Fe0a8eab341aaad8da25043f62c41%2Felephants-v-humans-42.jpg" class="img" alt="Chamunolwa Jimayi, 29, of the Elephant Response Team, watches a herd retreat into the bush after being driven out of the Linda neighborhood of Livingstone, Zambia." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Chamunolwa Jimayi, 29, of the Elephant Response Team, watches a herd retreat into the bush after being driven out of the Linda neighborhood of Livingstone, Zambia.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Tommy Trenchard for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;A brief standoff ensues as Jimayi and the elephant size each other up, neither willing to back down. "Easy boy, back you go," he shouts through the open window. A few moments later, the elephant starts to run. Revving his engine, Jimayi pursues it through the streets of Linda, turning this way and that to channel it away from the settlement until eventually it ducks beneath a footbridge and disappears into the darkness in the direction of the national park.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;The Elephant Response Team gets going&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;This has been Jimayi's life since 2019 when the Elephant Response Team was launched by a small Livingstone-based nonprofit, the Conservation and Tourism Society, in response to what was already, long before the drought began, a growing problem of human-wildlife conflict. With a total budget of barely $40,000 per year, CATS also helps search the national park for snares set by bushmeat poachers and carries out an extensive conservation education program designed primarily to teach people how to stay safe around elephants. The advice includes tips such as: always stay at least 300 feet from an elephant, never confront them and don't expect to outrun them: elephants can hit 28 mph.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-36672" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4000;         --source-height: 2667;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1000/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 1000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1300/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 1300w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/2000/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 2000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/2600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 2600w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 1238px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 60px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1000/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 1000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1300/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 1300w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/2000/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 2000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/2600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg 2600w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 1238px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 60px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 60px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd8%2Fc8%2F62316cbf4d179f21b272d0114baa%2Felephants-v-humans-31.jpg" class="img" alt="Chamunolwa Jimayi, 29, a driver for the Elephant Response Team, photographed in his vehicle at night in Livingstone, Zambia." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Chamunolwa Jimayi, 29, a driver for the Elephant Response Team, photographed in his vehicle at night in Livingstone, Zambia. "Sometimes we get more than 30 calls in a day," says Jimayi, who receives a stipend of around $140 a month.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Tommy Trenchard for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;They also teach residents about the different forms of elephant deterrents available to protect their homes and gardens, like reflector fences and "chili bricks" — a potent mix of elephant dung, used engine oil and fresh chili peppers that produces a noxious smoke when burned.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;The Elephant Response Team is based in Dambwa South, a neighborhood of single-story brick homes set in a maze of dusty streets on the edge of the National Park and one of the areas worst affected by human-wildlife conflict. Every evening through the long months of the dry season – typically between May and October -- children gather along the park perimeter to watch the daily exodus of wildlife crossing into town in search of food.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;p&gt;Crocodiles hunt for prey in sewage ponds, hippos lumber past industrial buildings, and zebras and buffalo graze contentedly by the roadside, seemingly oblivious to their human audience. From about 7 p.m. onward, elephants take over the streets.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;The park was once ringed by a fence but maintaining it has proved a challenge. Either it succumbs to elephant damage or is looted by residents looking to make a few dollars from the scrap metal. What remains are lines of empty fence poles and, here and there, a section of mangled wire flattened by the passage of animals. Park authorities say they are currently building a new one, with additional electric fencing in some areas, but Dominic Chiinda, director of the Department of National Parks and Wildlife, admits that a fence is unlikely to prove a lasting solution.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-36645" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4000;         --source-height: 2667;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F56%2F7b09a5884c539fa980828d6cdfe4%2Felephants-v-humans-04.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F56%2F7b09a5884c539fa980828d6cdfe4%2Felephants-v-humans-04.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1000/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F56%2F7b09a5884c539fa980828d6cdfe4%2Felephants-v-humans-04.jpg 1000w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1300/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F56%2F7b09a5884c539fa980828d6cdfe4%2Felephants-v-humans-04.jpg 1300w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2667+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F56%2F7b09a5884c539fa980828